					<head>Liturgy</head>
					<msContents class="lccn.loc.gov/n79090052" rend="visible">
						<summary>A collection of liturgical poems, Yemenite rite.</summary>
						<textLang mainLang="he" otherLangs="jrb"> </textLang>
						<msItem n="0" rend="visible" class="lccn.loc.gov/n79090052">
							<locus from="1r" to="230v"/>
							<title xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">Piyuṭim</title>
							<title xml:lang="he">פיוטים</title>
							<decoNote type="border">
								<locus n="2r"/>1 decorated title page, in red and black ink.</decoNote>
							<decoNote type="diagram">
								<locus n="2v"/>3 circular designs, in red and black ink.</decoNote>
							<note>
								<p>The poems were apparently in use in Yemen at the celebration of marriages and the rite of circumcision. Many pieces were composed by <name type="person" role="author">Shalem Shabezi</name> (b. 1619, d. 1686). Some of the poems include kabbalistic comments of various provenance.</p>
							</note>
							<author>
								<persName xml:lang="en" key="http://viaf.org/viaf/62734261">Shabazi, Shalem</persName>
								<persName xml:lang="he" key="http://viaf.org/viaf/62734261">שבזי, שלום בן יוסף</persName>
							</author>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="">
							<locus from="4r" to="67r"/>
							<title xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">Nashod</title>
							<note>
								<p>Contains 112 numbered pieces.</p>
							</note>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="">
							<locus from="67r" to="198r"/>
							<title xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">Shirot</title>
							<note>
